<section id="why">
  <div class="page">
    <span class="eyebrow reveal">Start Here</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">Why Build a <em>Raised Bed?</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">In-ground gardening works — but raised beds give you control over the things that are hardest to fix: soil quality, drainage, accessibility, and season length. Here's the full case for them.</p>
    <div class="why-grid">
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>🌱 You control the soil entirely</h4><p>Fill with exactly the mix you want — you're not working around clay, rocks, compaction, or chemical residue from what was planted there before. Every variable that matters starts in your hands.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>💧 Dramatically better drainage</h4><p>Raised beds drain far better than compacted ground. Roots never sit in standing water after heavy rain, which is one of the most common causes of plant failure in poorly-draining soil.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>🌡️ Warms up weeks earlier in spring</h4><p>The elevated soil mass warms faster than in-ground soil, letting you plant heat-loving crops like tomatoes and peppers earlier and extend your productive season at both ends.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>🦟 Far fewer weeds</h4><p>Filling with new soil means no existing weed seed bank. The defined edges make it easy to mulch heavily, and with consistent mulching, weeding in a raised bed drops to almost nothing after the first season.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>🦾 Easier on your body</h4><p>Even a 10-inch raised bed reduces bending significantly. A 24-inch bed can be worked almost entirely without bending at all. Over a full season, this difference is felt by everyone — not just people with mobility challenges.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>📐 More food per square foot</h4><p>Because you never walk on the growing area, soil stays loose and aerated. Closer plant spacing becomes viable, producing significantly more food per square foot than traditional row gardening in-ground.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>🐛 Easier pest management</h4><p>Defined borders are easier to protect — copper tape deters slugs, row covers can be supported above the frame, and beneficial nematodes applied to the soil stay concentrated in the bed rather than dispersing broadly.</p></div>
      <div class="why-card reveal"><h4>🔄 Better crop rotation</h4><p>Numbered or named beds make it easy to track exactly what grew where last season, making proper rotation — essential for preventing soil-borne disease buildup — simple to manage year after year.</p></div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">Raised Bed vs. In-Ground vs. Container</h3>
    <div class="scroll-x reveal">
      <table class="compare-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Raised Bed</th><th>In-Ground</th><th>Container / Pot</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Soil control</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Full</td><td class="chk-no">✗ Limited</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Full</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Drainage</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Excellent</td><td class="chk-mid">~ Variable</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Excellent</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Upfront cost</td><td class="chk-mid">~ Moderate</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Lowest</td><td class="chk-no">✗ High per sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Space efficiency</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ High</td><td class="chk-mid">~ Moderate</td><td class="chk-no">✗ Low</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Weed pressure</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Very low</td><td class="chk-no">✗ High</td><td class="chk-yes">✓ Minimal</td></tr>
