    <span class="eyebrow reveal">Step-by-Step Guide</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">How to Build a <em>Cedar 4×8 Bed</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">A 4×8 ft cedar raised bed is the most versatile starting point — large enough to grow a meaningful amount of food, small enough to reach every part without stepping inside. No power tools required; any lumber yard will make cuts for free or a few dollars.</p>
    <div class="build-meta reveal">
      <div class="meta-chip"><div class="m-val">~$65–90</div><div class="m-key">Material cost</div></div>
      <div class="meta-chip"><div class="m-val">1–2 hrs</div><div class="m-key">Build time</div></div>
      <div class="meta-chip"><div class="m-val">Beginner</div><div class="m-key">Skill level</div></div>
      <div class="meta-chip"><div class="m-val">10–15 yrs</div><div class="m-key">Lifespan (cedar)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="build-two-col">
      <div>
        <div class="steps">
          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">01</div><div><h3>Choose and prepare your location</h3><p>Find a spot with 6–8 hours of direct sun. Avoid low-lying areas that hold water after rain. Level the ground roughly — small dips are fine, but a slope of more than 6 inches from end to end will cause uneven drainage and drying. Mark out the footprint with stakes and string first to confirm placement before you start building.</p><div class="step-tip">💡 Walk the spot at noon and check where shadows fall. Taller plants (corn, staked tomatoes) go on the bed's north side so they don't shade shorter crops.</div></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">02</div><div><h3>Source and cut your lumber</h3><p>For a 4×8 ft bed at 10-inch depth, you need three 8-ft 2×10 cedar boards (two 8-ft sides, and one board cut in half to make two 4-ft ends) plus four 4×4 cedar posts cut to 12 inches each for corner supports. Ask the lumber yard to make all cuts — most do it for free or $1–2 per cut, saving you a saw entirely.</p><div class="step-tip">💡 Buy 10% more lumber than the calculation says. Cedar knots and splits near ends are common — having an extra foot of board prevents a wasted trip.</div><div class="step-warn">⚠️ Avoid "green" pressure-treated lumber with no date stamp — older stock may contain arsenic-based preservatives not suitable for food gardens.</div></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">03</div><div><h3>Pre-drill and assemble the frame</h3><p>Stand the two 4-ft end boards on their long edge. Clamp a 4×4 corner post flush to the inside of each end. Pre-drill two pilot holes through the long board into the post, then drive 3-inch exterior screws — this prevents cedar from splitting. Attach the 8-ft long boards to the remaining two posts the same way. You'll have a rectangular frame with posts sitting inside each corner.</p><div class="step-tip">💡 Assemble the frame next to where you'll place it. Fully-assembled 4×8 frames are awkward to carry — build it one section at a time and join them in place.</div></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">04</div><div><h3>Kill the ground cover beneath</h3><p>Lay the assembled frame in position. Trace the inside perimeter, then set the frame aside temporarily. Cover all the ground inside the outline with overlapping layers of cardboard (Amazon boxes work perfectly). Wet the cardboard thoroughly. This smothers existing grass and weeds without herbicide; the cardboard breaks down completely within one season and lets earthworms travel up into your bed.</p><div class="step-warn">⚠️ Do not use landscape fabric on the base of a raised bed. It blocks earthworms and beneficial organisms from entering your soil and causes drainage problems over time.</div></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">05</div><div><h3>Set and level the frame</h3><p>Place the frame on the wet cardboard. Drive the corner posts into the ground 3–4 inches with a rubber mallet — this anchors the bed against the soil settling over time. Place a spirit level diagonally across the frame in both directions. Shim low corners by digging away high spots or packing soil under low ones until it reads level in all directions.</p><div class="step-tip">💡 A few degrees of slope is fine. Perfectly level matters more for looks than function — just avoid visible lean that will show in the filled soil surface.</div></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">06</div><div><h3>Fill with the right soil mix</h3><p>The best general mix is 60% quality topsoil, 30% mature compost, and 10% perlite or coarse bark fines. Order in bulk if filling multiple beds — delivery by the cubic yard is far cheaper per unit than buying bagged soil. Fill to within 2 inches of the rim to leave room for mulch. See the full Soil Guide section below for deep detail on mixes and fill methods.</p><div class="step-tip">💡 A 4×8×10 in bed holds roughly 22–27 cubic feet of soil. Use the Cost Calculator on this page to get an exact number for your bed dimensions.</div></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">07</div><div><h3>Water thoroughly and let settle</h3><p>Before planting, water the entire bed deeply and let it rest 24 hours. Freshly filled soil has air pockets that will cause seedling roots to dry out if you plant immediately. After watering and settling, the soil level will drop 1–2 inches — top up to bring it back near the rim. This is also the moment to lay soaker hose or drip line before mulching if you want automated watering.</p></div></div>

          <div class="step reveal"><div class="step-num">08</div><div><h3>Add mulch and plant</h3><p>Apply 2–3 inches of straw, wood chip, or shredded leaf mulch around seedlings immediately after planting. Mulch is not optional in a raised bed — the elevated position means the soil surface dries out far faster than in-ground, and mulch is what keeps it workable between waterings. Leave a 1-inch gap between mulch and each plant stem to prevent collar rot.</p><div class="step-tip">💡 Your first harvest season will likely be your weakest as the soil biology establishes. Add a 2-inch compost top-dress each subsequent spring and the bed will improve noticeably year over year.</div></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="materials-box reveal">
          <h4>Materials — Standard 4×8 ft</h4>
          <div class="mat-row"><span class="mat-name">2×10 cedar boards, 8 ft long</span><span class="mat-qty">×3</span></div>
          <div class="mat-row"><span class="mat-name">4×4 cedar posts, cut to 12 in</span><span class="mat-qty">×4</span></div>
          <div class="mat-row"><span class="mat-name">3-in exterior screws</span><span class="mat-qty">24+</span></div>
          <div class="mat-row"><span class="mat-name">Flat cardboard (weed barrier)</span><span class="mat-qty">1 layer</span></div>
          <div class="mat-row"><span class="mat-name">Soil mix (60/30/10 blend)</span><span class="mat-qty">~25 cu ft</span></div>
          <div class="mat-row"><span class="mat-name">Mulch (straw or wood chip)</span><span class="mat-qty">~8 cu ft</span></div>
          <div class="tool-list">
            <h4 style="font-family:'Space Mono',monospace;font-size:0.62rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.12em;color:var(--cedar);margin-bottom:0.7rem;">Tools needed</h4>
            <div class="tool-row">Drill with #2 Phillips bit</div>
            <div class="tool-row">Rubber mallet</div>
            <div class="tool-row">Spirit level (2 ft+)</div>
            <div class="tool-row">Tape measure</div>
            <div class="tool-row">Clamps (optional but helpful)</div>
            <div class="tool-row">Garden hose</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">Common Build Mistakes to Avoid</h3>
    <div class="mistake-grid">
      <div class="mistake-card reveal"><h5>Boards too thin</h5><p>1×6 boards look fine at the lumber yard but flex significantly once soil pressure pushes outward. A 4×8 bed filled with 25 cu ft of soil exerts real pressure — 2× lumber is the minimum, and thicker boards need fewer braces.</p><div class="fix-tag">→ Use 2×8, 2×10, or 2×12 for beds over 3 ft wide</div></div>
      <div class="mistake-card reveal"><h5>No corner bracing</h5><p>Screwing boards directly end-to-end without interior corner posts creates a weak joint that bows outward within a season. The 4×4 corner post method described above is a permanent fix that also anchors the bed to the ground.</p><div class="fix-tag">→ Use 4×4 posts or steel L-brackets at every corner</div></div>
      <div class="mistake-card reveal"><h5>Filling with pure compost</h5><p>100% compost looks rich but compacts and shrinks dramatically as it dries, dropping several inches by midsummer. It also holds too much moisture when wet. Pure compost alone is a recipe for frustrating soil management.</p><div class="fix-tag">→ Max 30% compost in the mix — see Soil Guide</div></div>
      <div class="mistake-card reveal"><h5>Planting before soil settles</h5><p>Freshly filled soil has large air pockets. Transplants rooted in them dry out in 24 hours even when the top inch looks moist. Water thoroughly, wait a day, refill any significant settled areas, then plant.</p><div class="fix-tag">→ Water the bed and wait 24 hours before planting</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- BED TYPES -->
<section id="types">
  <div class="page">
    <span class="eyebrow reveal">Beyond the Rectangle</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">Types of <em>Raised Beds</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">The standard 4×8 rectangle is the right starting point for most gardeners, but different spaces and needs call for different shapes. Here's the full range.</p>
    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">▭</div><h4>Standard Rectangle</h4><p>The classic. 4×8 ft is the most efficient use of lumber (standard board lengths require no waste cuts) and gives enough space for a meaningful mixed planting. Easy to cover with row cover or a simple cold frame.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Best for most</span><span class="tspec">Easy to build</span><span class="tspec">Efficient lumber use</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">◻</div><h4>Square (4×4 ft)</h4><p>Accessible from all four sides without reaching. Ideal for a small space, a patio corner, or as a dedicated herb bed. Square-foot planting charts are designed around 4×4 beds.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Beginner friendly</span><span class="tspec">All-side access</span><span class="tspec">Small footprint</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">⌂</div><h4>Keyhole Bed</h4><p>A circular or D-shaped bed with a narrow path cut into the center, allowing you to reach the middle without ever stepping in. Particularly well-suited to compost-in-place growing where a central compost basket feeds the entire bed.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">High efficiency</span><span class="tspec">Built-in composting</span><span class="tspec">Harder to build</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">⌐</div><h4>L-Shaped</h4><p>Two beds joined at a corner — great for fitting into the corner of a yard or against two walls. Creates a natural seating or potting area in the interior angle. Build as two separate rectangles joined with shared corner posts.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Corner spaces</span><span class="tspec">Two micro-zones</span><span class="tspec">More lumber needed</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">≡</div><h4>Tiered / Pyramid</h4><p>Multiple stacked levels stepping up from large to small. Creates three different planting zones (different depths for different crops), drains excellently, and serves as a focal garden feature. Usually bought as a kit rather than built from scratch.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Decorative</span><span class="tspec">Multi-depth zones</span><span class="tspec">Compact footprint</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">🌿</div><h4>Hugelkultur Mound</h4><p>A no-frame raised bed built by mounding logs and branches topped with soil and compost. As the wood decomposes underground it feeds the bed for years and retains moisture remarkably well in dry climates. No lumber cost at all — just sourced wood and soil.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Low cost</span><span class="tspec">Self-feeding</span><span class="tspec">No frame needed</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">🦽</div><h4>Elevated / Table Height</h4><p>A bed built on legs at standing height (28–36 inches) for fully accessible gardening with no bending. Usually requires a kit or more complex frame construction. Excellent for anyone with back issues, mobility limitations, or who gardens from a wheelchair.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Fully accessible</span><span class="tspec">No bending</span><span class="tspec">Higher cost</span></div></div>
      <div class="type-card reveal"><div class="type-icon">🛗</div><h4>Vertical / Trellis Bed</h4><p>A narrow raised bed (1–2 ft wide) built against a wall or fence, with a built-in or wall-mounted trellis behind it. Uses minimal horizontal space while growing climbing crops (beans, cucumbers, peas) vertically. Great for urban gardens or fence lines.</p><div class="type-specs"><span class="tspec">Space saving</span><span class="tspec">Climbing crops</span><span class="tspec">Against walls/fences</span></div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SIZING -->
<section id="sizes">
  <div class="page">
    <span class="eyebrow reveal">Dimensions Matter</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">Choosing the Right <em>Size & Depth</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">Width determines reachability; length affects lumber cost and waste; depth controls what you can grow. Getting these right before you build saves you rebuilding later.</p>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal" style="margin-top:0;">The width rule: never wider than 4 ft</h3>
    <p class="reveal" style="font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.75;max-width:660px;margin-bottom:2rem;">The most important dimension is width, not length. A bed wider than 4 feet means you'll have to step into the growing area to reach the middle — which compacts the soil and defeats one of the main advantages of raised beds. If space allows, two 3-ft-wide beds with a path between them outperform one 6-ft-wide bed.</p>
    <div class="size-grid">
      <div class="size-card reveal"><div class="size-header"><div class="size-dims">2 × 4 ft</div><div class="size-label">Starter / Kids</div></div><div class="size-body"><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Reach from one side</span><span class="s-val">Full bed</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Soil needed (10 in)</span><span class="s-val">~6 cu ft</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Boards needed</span><span class="s-val">2× 8 ft + cuts</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Good for</span><span class="s-val">Herbs, lettuce</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Lumber cost est.</span><span class="s-val">~$15–25</span></div></div></div>
      <div class="size-card reveal"><div class="size-header"><div class="size-dims">4 × 4 ft</div><div class="size-label">Small / Compact</div></div><div class="size-body"><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Reach from all sides</span><span class="s-val">Full bed</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Soil needed (10 in)</span><span class="s-val">~12 cu ft</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Boards needed</span><span class="s-val">2× 8 ft, each halved</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Good for</span><span class="s-val">Salad, herbs, 9 crops</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Lumber cost est.</span><span class="s-val">~$25–40</span></div></div></div>
      <div class="size-card reveal" style="border-color:var(--cedar);"><div class="size-header" style="background:var(--cedar);"><div class="size-dims" style="color:var(--ink);">4 × 8 ft</div><div class="size-label" style="color:rgba(0,0,0,0.45);">Most Popular ★</div></div><div class="size-body"><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Reach from both sides</span><span class="s-val">Full width</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Soil needed (10 in)</span><span class="s-val">~22–27 cu ft</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Boards needed</span><span class="s-val">3× 8 ft boards</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Good for</span><span class="s-val">Mixed vegetables</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Lumber cost est.</span><span class="s-val">~$55–80</span></div></div></div>
      <div class="size-card reveal"><div class="size-header"><div class="size-dims">4 × 12 ft</div><div class="size-label">Large / Productive</div></div><div class="size-body"><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Reach from both sides</span><span class="s-val">Full width</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Soil needed (10 in)</span><span class="s-val">~38–42 cu ft</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Boards needed</span><span class="s-val">4× 8 ft + joins</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Good for</span><span class="s-val">Corn, full families</span></div><div class="size-stat"><span class="s-key">Lumber cost est.</span><span class="s-val">~$90–130</span></div></div></div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">How deep does it need to be?</h3>
    <div class="depth-grid">
      <div class="depth-card reveal"><h4>6 inches <span class="depth-inches">— 1× 2×6</span></h4><p>Suitable for salad greens, herbs, radishes, and shallow annuals. Roots reach the native soil below for additional depth but moisture retention is poor. Not enough for tomatoes, peppers, or anything with a significant root system.</p></div>
      <div class="depth-card reveal"><h4>10–12 inches <span class="depth-inches">— 1× 2×10 or 2×12</span></h4><p>The sweet spot for almost all summer vegetables — tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, beans, squash, and shallow root crops like beets and radishes. The most common and recommended depth for a first raised bed.</p></div>
      <div class="depth-card reveal"><h4>18–20 inches <span class="depth-inches">— 2× stacked 2×10</span></h4><p>Excellent for deep root crops like carrots, parsnips, and potatoes. Also more accessible ergonomically — less bending than a 10-inch bed. Requires nearly double the soil volume and cost, but a meaningful upgrade for serious growing.</p></div>
      <div class="depth-card reveal"><h4>24–30 inches <span class="depth-inches">— Table-height build</span></h4><p>Designed for fully accessible gardening — workable from a standing position or wheelchair with no bending at all. Requires a more robust frame (usually legs rather than corner posts) or a dedicated kit. Often the right answer when accessibility is the primary goal.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="access-note reveal">
      <div class="an-icon">♿</div>
      <div><h4>Accessibility note</h4><p>If reduced mobility is part of your situation, the height of the bed matters as much as its size. A 24-30 inch bed on a firm path eliminates nearly all the bending and kneeling that makes in-ground gardening difficult. Pair with a 2-ft-wide bed (reachable from one side without moving) and you can work the entire bed from a single standing or seated position.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SOIL GUIDE -->
<section id="soil">
  <div class="page">
    <span class="eyebrow reveal" style="color:var(--wood);">The Foundation</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">The <em>Soil Guide</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">Soil is where most raised bed budgets and most raised bed failures happen. The wrong fill turns a good structure into a frustrating planting box. Here's exactly what to put in yours.</p>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal" style="margin-top:0;">The ideal mix: the 60-30-10 rule</h3>
    <div class="soil-recipe reveal">
      <div class="recipe-title">Standard raised bed fill — per cubic yard</div>
      <div class="recipe-bar"><div class="rb-label"><span class="rb-name">Quality topsoil</span><span class="rb-pct">60%</span></div><div class="rb-track"><div class="rb-fill" style="width:60%"></div></div></div>
      <div class="recipe-bar"><div class="rb-label"><span class="rb-name">Mature compost</span><span class="rb-pct">30%</span></div><div class="rb-track"><div class="rb-fill green" style="width:30%"></div></div></div>
      <div class="recipe-bar"><div class="rb-label"><span class="rb-name">Perlite or bark fines (aeration)</span><span class="rb-pct">10%</span></div><div class="rb-track"><div class="rb-fill gray" style="width:10%"></div></div></div>
      <div class="recipe-note">This ratio drains well, retains moisture between waterings, and provides a full growing season of nutrition without burning roots. It improves each year as organic matter breaks down and you top-dress with fresh compost.</div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">What each ingredient does</h3>
    <div class="soil-grid">
      <div class="soil-card reveal"><div class="soil-tag">60% of the mix</div><h4>Quality Topsoil</h4><p>The structural base. Provides mineral content and weight that holds roots in place. Avoid ultra-cheap bulk topsoil (often clay-heavy and compaction-prone) and pure "garden soil" bags (usually too light). Look for screened topsoil with visible texture and a dark, earthy smell.</p></div>
      <div class="soil-card reveal"><div class="soil-tag">30% of the mix</div><h4>Mature Compost</h4><p>The nutrition and biology engine of the bed. Feeds plants slowly, improves structure, and introduces beneficial microbes. Must be fully mature (no recognizable ingredients, dark, crumbly, smells like forest floor). Green compost burns roots. Add a 2-inch top-dress of fresh compost every spring.</p></div>
      <div class="soil-card reveal"><div class="soil-tag">10% of the mix</div><h4>Perlite or Bark Fines</h4><p>Creates aeration channels that prevent compaction over time. Perlite (the white volcanic glass bits) is the most reliable — it never breaks down. Coarse bark fines or horticultural grit work too. Skip this and your bed soil will gradually compact into something approaching clay by year three.</p></div>
      <div class="soil-card reveal"><div class="soil-tag">Optional addition</div><h4>Worm Castings</h4><p>Gentle, slow-release nutrition that won't burn seedling roots. Add a small amount (5–10% of the compost portion) at planting time in beds where you're starting from seed. Expensive to buy in volume but dramatically improves germination rates.</p></div>
      <div class="soil-card reveal"><div class="soil-tag">For root crops</div><h4>Coarse Sand</h4><p>Replacing some of the perlite with coarse horticultural sand improves drainage and looseness for root vegetables like carrots and parsnips, which need to push through easily. Never use builder's sand or beach sand — the particle size is wrong and it creates a cement-like mix.</p></div>
      <div class="soil-card reveal"><div class="soil-tag">pH adjustment</div><h4>Garden Lime or Sulfur</h4><p>Add garden lime to raise pH toward 6.5–7.0 for most vegetables, or sulfur to lower pH for acid-lovers like blueberries. Test before adding — most bagged topsoil is already close to neutral. A simple $10 soil test kit from a hardware store gives you the full picture.</p></div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">Budget fill methods</h3>
    <div class="fill-methods">
      <div class="fill-card reveal"><h4><span class="fill-icon">📦</span>Bagged mix</h4><p>The most convenient but most expensive per cubic foot. Works well for small beds (under 20 cu ft). Look for bags labeled "raised bed mix" — usually a pre-blended version of the 60/30/10 recipe. Check the ingredients; bags that list "composted bark" as the main ingredient are mostly filler.</p><div class="fill-cost">Cost: $8–12 per cu ft bagged</div></div>
      <div class="fill-card reveal"><h4><span class="fill-icon">🚛</span>Bulk delivery</h4><p>Order topsoil and compost by the cubic yard from a local landscape supply company — almost always 40–60% cheaper per unit than bags. Most companies deliver with a dump truck and can place it close to your bed. One cubic yard (27 cu ft) fills a standard 4×8×10 in bed almost exactly.</p><div class="fill-cost">Cost: $35–60 per cu yd delivered</div></div>
      <div class="fill-card reveal"><h4><span class="fill-icon">🆓</span>Hugelkultur base layer</h4><p>Fill the bottom third of a deep bed with logs, branches, wood chips, and leaves before adding your soil mix on top. The buried wood acts as a slow-release sponge and nutrient source as it decomposes over 3–5 years, dramatically reducing how much soil you need to buy and improving moisture retention.</p><div class="fill-cost">Cost: Free (uses natural material) + less soil needed</div></div>
      <div class="fill-card reveal"><h4><span class="fill-icon">🌳</span>Municipal compost programs</h4><p>Many cities sell compost and wood-chip mulch from yard waste programs at heavily discounted prices — often $10–20 per cubic yard compared to $50+ retail. Some programs give it away free for pickup. Search your city name + "free compost" or "yard waste compost" to find local programs.</p><div class="fill-cost">Cost: $0–20 per cu yd (program dependent)</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- WATERING -->
<section id="water">
  <div class="page">
    <span class="eyebrow reveal">Irrigation Guide</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">Watering Your <em>Raised Bed</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">Raised beds dry out faster than in-ground soil. The good news: a simple soaker hose under mulch eliminates most of the daily work. Here's how to water smart.</p>
    <div class="water-grid">
      <div class="water-card reveal"><h4>💧 Hand watering</h4><p>The simplest approach — a watering wand with a gentle rose head. Good for small beds or when you want close contact with plants to spot problems early. Requires daily attention in summer; easy to under-water roots with a shallow splash.</p><div class="w-verdict">Best for: 1–2 small beds, close inspection gardening</div></div>
      <div class="water-card reveal"><h4>🔄 Soaker hose</h4><p>A rubber or canvas hose that weeps water along its full length when connected to a standard spigot. Lay it in an S-pattern across the bed and bury under 2–3 inches of mulch. Delivers water directly to roots, cuts disease from wet foliage, and can be left on a timer.</p><div class="w-verdict">Best for: Most raised beds — the highest value upgrade</div></div>
      <div class="water-card reveal"><h4>💦 Drip irrigation</h4><p>Individual drip emitters on flexible tubing, one per plant. More precise than soaker hose — each emitter can be calibrated to a different flow rate. More complex to set up but dramatically reduces water waste in larger gardens with many beds.</p><div class="w-verdict">Best for: Multiple beds, serious vegetable production</div></div>
      <div class="water-card reveal"><h4>⏱️ Timer-controlled system</h4><p>Any of the above systems connected to a battery-powered hose timer ($15–35). Set it once and the bed waters itself on a fixed schedule regardless of whether you're home. The single biggest time-saver in a raised bed garden.</p><div class="w-verdict">Best for: Busy schedules, vacation watering, consistency</div></div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">Setting up a soaker hose in 5 steps</h3>
    <div class="drip-steps reveal">
      <div class="drip-step"><div class="drip-num">1</div><div>Connect a Y-splitter to your outdoor spigot, so you can still use the hose normally alongside the soaker system.</div></div>
      <div class="drip-step"><div class="drip-num">2</div><div>Run regular garden hose from the spigot to the edge of your bed — only soaker hose runs inside the planting area.</div></div>
      <div class="drip-step"><div class="drip-num">3</div><div>Lay soaker hose in an S or zigzag pattern across the bed, 6–8 inches apart. Cap the far end with the included end cap.</div></div>
      <div class="drip-step"><div class="drip-num">4</div><div>Cover the soaker hose with 2–3 inches of mulch — this keeps the soil surface from crusting and reduces evaporation by 50%+.</div></div>
      <div class="drip-step"><div class="drip-num">5</div><div>Attach a timer to the spigot. Water deeply for 30–45 minutes, 3–4 times per week in summer. Adjust based on how quickly your specific soil dries.</div></div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="sub-title reveal">How often to water by season</h3>
    <div class="scroll-x reveal">
      <table class="season-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Season / Conditions</th><th>Frequency</th><th>Duration</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Spring (cool, wet)</td><td>1–2× per week</td><td>20–25 min</td><td>Check soil 2 inches down — if moist, skip. Seedlings need consistency but not saturation.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Early Summer</td><td>2–3× per week</td><td>25–35 min</td><td>As temperatures rise, increase frequency before plants show stress. Mulch now if you haven't already.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Peak Summer (hot/dry)</td><td>3–4× per week</td><td>35–45 min</td><td>Heat above 90°F can require daily watering in some climates, especially for containers within the bed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Heat Wave (95°F+)</td><td>Daily</td><td>30–40 min</td><td>Water in the early morning. Afternoon wilting is often heat stress, not water shortage — check soil before adding water.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Late Summer / Fall</td><td>2–3× per week</td><td>25–35 min</td><td>Reduce as crops finish. Fall transplants need consistent watering for the first 2–3 weeks as roots establish.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

