    <h3 class="sub-title reveal" style="margin-top:3rem;">Succession Sowing — Getting Continuous Harvests</h3>
    <p class="reveal" style="font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.75;max-width:660px;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Instead of planting everything at once and drowning in one crop, stagger plantings so harvests spread across weeks. A single 4×8 bed can produce fresh food almost continuously from spring through fall with good succession planning.</p>
    <div class="succession-grid">
      <div class="succ-card reveal">
        <h4>🥬 Lettuce & Salad Greens</h4>
        <p>Sow a short row every 2 weeks from early spring through late summer. Each row gives you a 2–3 week harvest window before it bolts. Overlap timing so a fresh row is always approaching peak as the previous one finishes.</p>
        <div class="succ-interval">Every 14 days · Stop 6 weeks before first frost</div>
      </div>
      <div class="succ-card reveal">
        <h4>🫘 Bush Beans</h4>
        <p>Each sowing produces one main flush of pods over 2–3 weeks, then slows. Sow a short row every 2–3 weeks from last frost until 8 weeks before first fall frost. Three staggered sowings keep beans coming all summer.</p>
        <div class="succ-interval">Every 18–21 days · 3–4 rounds through summer</div>
      </div>
      <div class="succ-card reveal">
        <h4>🌿 Cilantro & Dill</h4>
        <p>Both bolt quickly in heat. Sow a small cluster every 3 weeks — as one row sends up a flower stalk, the next one is just hitting peak leaf production. Let one plant go to seed in fall to self-sow next year.</p>
        <div class="succ-interval">Every 21 days · Year-round in mild climates</div>
      </div>
      <div class="succ-card reveal">
        <h4>🥕 Carrots</h4>
        <p>Carrots can stay in the ground for weeks after maturity without deteriorating — use them as a "living pantry." Sow a row every 3–4 weeks for rolling harvests. Thin well after germination; crowded carrots produce forked, small roots.</p>
        <div class="succ-interval">Every 21–28 days · Stop 10 weeks before frost</div>
      </div>
      <div class="succ-card reveal">
        <h4>🫛 Peas</h4>
        <p>Peas hate summer heat. Sow early spring as soon as soil can be worked, then stop — they'll fail in midsummer. Sow again in late summer for a fall harvest, 10–12 weeks before your first expected frost date.</p>
        <div class="succ-interval">Spring & late summer only · 2 rounds per year</div>
      </div>
      <div class="succ-card reveal">
        <h4>🌱 Radishes</h4>
        <p>The fastest succession crop in the bed — 25 days from seed to harvest. Scatter a small patch every 10–14 days between slower-growing plants. They double as a space holder and can even be used as a pest sacrifice crop.</p>
        <div class="succ-interval">Every 10–14 days · Prolific spring and fall</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PESTS & DISEASE -->
<section id="pests">
  <div class="page">
    <span class="eyebrow reveal">Protection Guide</span>
    <h2 class="big-title reveal">Pests & Disease <em>in Raised Beds</em></h2>
    <p class="intro reveal">Raised beds genuinely reduce pest pressure compared to in-ground growing — better airflow reduces fungal problems, defined edges slow ground-level pests, and healthy, well-drained soil produces more resilient plants. But they don't eliminate problems. Here's what to watch for and exactly what to do.</p>

    <h3 class="sub-title reveal" style="color:var(--white);">Common Pests</h3>
    <div class="pest-grid">
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-h">High</span>
        <h4>Aphids</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Tomatoes · Peppers · Beans · Cucumbers</span>
        <p>Tiny soft-bodied insects clustered on new growth and undersides of leaves. Excrete sticky honeydew that attracts ants and encourages mold. Populations explode fast in warm weather if unchecked.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Blast off with a firm water jet each morning for 3–5 days. Introduce ladybugs or lacewings — one ladybug eats up to 5,000 aphids in its lifetime. Neem oil spray for persistent colonies. Check ants too — they "farm" aphid colonies and will fight off natural predators.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-h">High</span>
        <h4>Slugs & Snails</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Lettuce · Seedlings · Strawberries · Brassicas</span>
        <p>Most active at night and after rain. Raised beds reduce (but don't eliminate) slug pressure — wooden frames can harbor them, especially in gaps under the boards. Look for silvery slime trails on leaves.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Copper tape around the top edge of the bed frame — effective and long-lasting. Iron phosphate slug bait scattered sparingly around plants (safe for pets and wildlife). Beer traps work well: small containers filled with cheap beer sunk to ground level.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-h">High</span>
        <h4>Tomato Hornworm</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Tomatoes · Peppers · Eggplant</span>
        <p>Large green caterpillar (up to 4 inches) perfectly camouflaged against tomato stems. Can strip a plant of leaves overnight. Look for large, dark droppings at the base of the plant as the first sign.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Hand-pick at dusk when they're most active. Check undersides of leaves and around stems. Drop into soapy water. Braconid wasps parasitize them naturally — white cocoons on the back of a hornworm mean it's already dying; leave those ones in place.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-m">Medium</span>
        <h4>Flea Beetles</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Eggplant · Brassicas · Potatoes · Radishes</span>
        <p>Tiny black beetles that jump when disturbed and leave small round holes in leaves. Young seedlings are most vulnerable — established plants usually outgrow the damage. Worst in warm, dry spring weather.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Row cover over transplants for the first 2–3 weeks protects seedlings through the most vulnerable stage. Diatomaceous earth dusted around the bed edge deters them. Sacrificial radishes nearby as a trap crop.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-m">Medium</span>
        <h4>Cabbage White Caterpillars</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Broccoli · Cabbage · Kale · Brussels Sprouts</span>
        <p>The small green caterpillars of the white cabbage butterfly — they match the leaf color exactly and are hard to spot until damage is significant. Check the undersides of leaves for pale yellow egg clusters.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Fine mesh insect-proof netting over brassicas is the most reliable prevention. Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) spray kills caterpillars without harming other insects and breaks down quickly in sunlight.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-m">Medium</span>
        <h4>Squash Vine Borer</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Zucchini · Squash · Pumpkin</span>
        <p>Moth larvae that tunnel into the base of zucchini and squash stems, causing the plant to wilt suddenly as if from drought. Often by the time you see the problem, significant damage is done. Look for sawdust-like frass at the stem base.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Row cover from transplanting until flowers open. Wrap stem bases in foil or nylon. Succession plant a second sowing mid-season — if the first is destroyed, the second establishes before borers lay again. 'Tromboncino' squash has natural resistance.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-l">Low–Medium</span>
        <h4>Spider Mites</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Most crops in hot, dry conditions</span>
        <p>Microscopic mites that cause a fine stippling on leaves, eventually turning them bronze and papery. Fine webbing on leaf undersides is the tell-tale sign. Worst during dry heat waves when plants are already stressed.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Well-watered, mulched plants are far less susceptible — moisture stress is the biggest contributing factor. Spray leaf undersides forcefully with water. Insecticidal soap as a last resort.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pest-card reveal">
        <span class="sev sev-l">Low</span>
        <h4>Cutworms</h4>
        <span class="pest-target">Seedlings · Transplants</span>
        <p>Fat, soil-dwelling caterpillars that cut young seedlings off at the base overnight, leaving them lying beside the hole like a tiny felled tree. Mostly a spring problem when new transplants go in.</p>
        <div class="pest-fix"><strong>Fix:</strong> Place a cardboard or tin-foil collar around each transplant, pushed 1 inch into the soil and standing 2 inches above it — blocks the cutting. Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) soil drench kills larvae in the soil.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="sub-title reveal" style="color:var(--white);margin-top:3rem;">Common Diseases</h3>
    <div class="disease-grid">
      <div class="disease-card reveal">
        <h4>Blossom End Rot</h4>
        <p>Dark, sunken, leathery patches on the bottom of tomatoes, peppers, and squash. Looks like a calcium deficiency but is almost always caused by inconsistent watering disrupting calcium uptake — not a lack of calcium in the soil.</p>
        <div class="d-prevent">Fix: Fix your watering schedule before adding supplements. Consistent deep watering and mulch solve 95% of cases.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="disease-card reveal">
        <h4>Powdery Mildew</h4>
        <p>White, talcum-powder-like coating on leaves. Very common on cucumbers, squash, and peas in late summer. Rarely kills plants but reduces productivity. Spreads in humid conditions with poor airflow.</p>
        <div class="d-prevent">Fix: Space plants properly for airflow, water at the base only. A diluted milk spray (40% milk, 60% water) applied weekly prevents spread on mild cases.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="disease-card reveal">
        <h4>Early Blight (Tomato)</h4>
        <p>Brown spots with yellow halos on lower tomato leaves, working upward through the season. Caused by a fungus that splashes up from soil onto leaves. Doesn't kill plants but causes early defoliation that weakens yield.</p>
        <div class="d-prevent">Fix: Mulch under plants (stops soil splash), remove affected leaves promptly, avoid overhead watering. Copper-based fungicide spray slows but doesn't cure it.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="disease-card reveal">
        <h4>Damping Off</h4>
        <p>Seedlings that keel over at soil level as if cut. Caused by soil-borne fungal pathogens, almost always in overwatered conditions. Most common in seed trays and very young transplants.</p>
        <div class="d-prevent">Fix: Never overwater seedlings. Ensure excellent drainage in seed trays. Water from below (bottom-watering) keeps the surface dry and hostile to damping-off fungi.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="disease-card reveal">
        <h4>Fusarium / Verticillium Wilt</h4>
        <p>Sudden wilting of one side of a plant — often just a few branches at first — despite adequate water. Caused by soil-borne fungi that clog the plant's vascular system. No cure once infected.</p>
        <div class="d-prevent">Prevention only: Crop rotation is the only reliable defense — don't grow tomatoes or peppers in the same bed more than once every 3 years. Remove infected plants entirely.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="disease-card reveal">
        <h4>Club Root (Brassicas)</h4>
        <p>Brassica plants wilt during the day and recover at night; roots are swollen and distorted when pulled. Caused by a soil-borne protist that persists for 20+ years in infected soil. Worst in acidic, wet conditions.</p>
        <div class="d-prevent">Fix: Lime the soil to raise pH above 7.0 — club root is far less active in alkaline conditions. Rotate brassicas out of affected beds; consider replacing bed soil if severely infected.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

