          <tr><td>Untreated Douglas Fir</td><td>$</td><td>5–8 yrs</td><td class="safe-yes">✓ Yes</td><td>The budget entry point. No rot resistance so it will eventually soften from the bottom up, but it's the cheapest safe option for a first bed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Redwood (Heart grade)</td><td>$$$</td><td>20–25 yrs</td><td class="safe-yes">✓ Yes</td><td>Outstanding natural durability. Hard to source outside the western US and increasingly expensive. Worth it if you can get it at a reasonable price.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Untreated Pine</td><td>$</td><td>3–5 yrs</td><td class="safe-yes">✓ Yes</td><td>The shortest-lived option. Rots quickly from the bottom where it contacts moist soil. Fine for a temporary or trial bed but plan to replace it.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ACQ Pressure-Treated (post-2004)</td><td>$</td><td>25+ yrs</td><td class="safe-maybe">⚠️ Debated</td><td>Modern treatment uses copper compounds, not arsenic. Most research shows negligible leaching into soil. If concerned, line inner walls with heavy polythene, leaving the base open. Avoid old green-tinted stock.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Galvanized Steel (corrugated)</td><td>$$</td><td>20–30 yrs</td><td class="safe-yes">✓ Yes</td><td>Very durable, no rot, modern industrial look. Heats up in direct sun, potentially baking root zones in hot climates — mitigate with a thin foam or cardboard liner on inner walls.</td></tr>
